TDI Finalist Interview - diving into the H-1B visa¶

What is the H-1B visa?¶

The US H-1B visa is a non-immigrant visa that allows US companies to employ graduate level workers in specialty occupations that require theoretical or technical expertise in specialized fields such as IT, finance, accounting, architecture, engineering, science, medicine, etc.

Preliminary EDA and Machine Learning Model¶

In this notebook, I will expand on the themes I proposed during the semi-final 'challenge' round. In a separate notebook, I scraped all job titles with more than 1,000 entries (307 total job titles) from the website https://h1bdata.info.

During the semi-final challenge, I looked at salary trends for Data Scientists and top states were the most H1-B visas were granted to data scientists. During this data exploration, I will:

  • Look at more general geographical trends for all top job positions
  • Check salary trends for popular tech jobs
  • Compare granted vs denied applications
  • Compare typical wait periods for visa applications for jobs with most entries
  • Check tech industry job trends (e.g. are particular positions trending lower/higher during the past 5 years?)

Extract features 'city' and 'state' from 'location'¶

In [5]:
# Note: this function requires a cleaned up 'location' column with no NaN or empty strings
def get_city_state(df):
    df["state"] = df["location"].str.split().str[-1]
    df["location"].apply(lambda x: "".join(x.split()[1:]))
    df["location"] = df["location"].apply(lambda x: x.split(" "))
    df["city"] = df["location"].str[:-1].apply(lambda x: " ".join(x))
    
    df = df[['employer', 'job title', 'base salary', 'submit date',
       'start date', 'case status', 'submit year', 'submit month', 'state', 'city']]
    
    return df

def filter_job_titles(df, job_title_list):
    df_return = pd.DataFrame()
    list_ = []
    for title in job_title_list:
        df_tmp = df[df['job title']==title]
        list_.append(df_tmp)
        
    df_return = pd.concat(list_)
    return df_return

In [13]:
def plot_salaries(df, linestyles,linecolors):
    line_titles = []
    for i in range(df.shape[1]):
        line_titles.append(df.columns[i])

    fig2, ax2 = plt.subplots(figsize=(13,8))

    for i, column in enumerate(df.columns):
        ax2.plot(df[column],linestyle=linestyles[i],color=linecolors[i],linewidth=3)

    ax2.legend(line_titles,loc='upper left',frameon=True)
    ax2.set_title('Median Base Salaries',fontweight='bold')
    ax2.set_axis_bgcolor('white')
    y_formatter = ticker.StrMethodFormatter('${x:,.0f}')
    x_formatter = ticker.FormatStrFormatter('%1.0f')
    ax2.yaxis.set_major_formatter(y_formatter)
    ax2.xaxis.set_major_formatter(x_formatter)
    ax2.grid(b=True,which='major',axis='both',color='k',linestyle='--',linewidth=0.5)

In [23]:
def visas_not_certified(df):
    index = np.arange(len(df['NOT CERTIFIED']))
    df['% NOT CERTIFIED'] = round(df['NOT CERTIFIED']/(df['CERTIFIED']+df['NOT CERTIFIED'])*100,2)
    
    width=0.4
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (8,6))
    ax.bar(index-2*width/3, df['% NOT CERTIFIED'], width)
    
    df['avg not cert'] = (df['% NOT CERTIFIED'].mean())
    line = df['avg not cert'].plot(linestyle='--', color='r')
    
    ax.set_ylabel('Not Certified / Total H-1B applications (%)')
    ax.set_title('Percentage of visas not certified (%)')
    ax.set_xticks(index)
    ax.text(index[0], df['avg not cert'].values[0]+0.1, 'average', color='red', fontweight='bold')
    ax.set_axis_bgcolor('white')
    ax.set_xlim(-0.5,8.5)
    ax.set_xticklabels(tuple(df.index.get_values()),rotation=45, ha='right')
    plt.show()

def top_states(df):   
    index = np.arange(len(df['issued']))
    width = 0.4
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8,8))
    
    rect1 = ax.bar(index-3*width/2, df['issued'], width, color='Blue', label = 'Visas issued')
    rect2 = ax.bar(index-width/2, df['employers'], width, color='Red', label = '# of employers sponsoring visas')
    
    ax.set_ylabel('Visas issued (blue) and employers issuing (red) per state')
    ax.set_title('Top 10 states issuing H-1B visas, by visas issued')
    ax.set_xticks(index-width/2)
    ax.set_xticklabels(tuple(df.index.get_values()))
    ax.set_axis_bgcolor('white')
    ax.legend()
    
    if df['issued'].max() > 10000:
        for i, v in enumerate(df['issued']):
            if v < 100000:
                ax.text(index[i]-2.5*width/2, v+14000, str(v), color='blue',rotation=90, fontweight='bold')
            else:
                ax.text(index[i]-2.5*width/2, v+16000, str(v), color='blue',rotation=90, fontweight='bold')

        for i, v in enumerate(df['employers']):
            if v < 10000:
                ax.text(index[i]-width/3.5, v+11000, str(v), color='red',rotation=90, fontweight='bold')
            else:
                ax.text(index[i]-width/3.5, v+14000, str(v), color='red',rotation=90, fontweight='bold')

    if df['issued'].max() < 10000:
        for i, v in enumerate(df['issued']):
            if v < 1000:
                ax.text(index[i]-2.5*width/2, v+85, str(v), color='blue',rotation=90, fontweight='bold')
            else:
                ax.text(index[i]-2.5*width/2, v+120, str(v), color='blue',rotation=90, fontweight='bold')

        for i, v in enumerate(df['employers']):
            if v < 100:
                ax.text(index[i]-width/3.5, v+50, str(v), color='red',rotation=90, fontweight='bold')
            else:
                ax.text(index[i]-width/3.5, v+100, str(v), color='red',rotation=90, fontweight='bold')
                
    plt.show()

Create functions (for now) to transform and inverse transform dataframes¶

Use functions to facilitate multiple dataframe transformations. Look into creating a class that does this later, rather than a series of separate functions.

In [38]:
def fit_and_transform(df,cols_to_transf):
    df_transf = df[cols_to_transf]
    df_non_transf = df.drop(cols_to_transf, axis = 1)
    
    fit = df_transf.apply(lambda x: d[x.name].fit_transform(x))
    
    df = pd.concat([fit, df_non_transf], axis=1, join='outer')
    return df
In [39]:
def inverse_encoding(df,encoded_cols):
    df_inverse = df[encoded_cols]
    df_non_inv = df.drop(encoded_cols, axis = 1)
    
    df_inverse = df_inverse.apply(lambda x: d[x.name].inverse_transform(x))
    df = pd.concat([df_inverse, df_non_inv], axis=1, join='outer')
    
    return df
In [40]:
def encode_future_data(df,cols_to_transf):
    df_transf = df[cols_to_transf]
    df_non_transf = df.drop(cols_to_transf, axis = 1)
    
    fit = df_transf.apply(lambda x: d[x.name].transform(x))
    
    df = pd.concat([fit, df_non_transf], axis=1, join='outer')
    return df

def preprocess_new_data(dict,cols_to_transf,future_data_column_order):
    predict_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(predict_dict)
    predict_df_transf = predict_df[cols_to_transf]
    predict_df_non_transf = predict_df.drop(cols_to_transf, axis=1)
    
    for col in predict_df_transf.columns:
        predict_df_transf[col] = predict_df_transf[col].str.upper()
    
    predict_df = pd.concat([predict_df_transf, predict_df_non_transf], axis=1, join='outer')
    
    predict_df = encode_future_data(predict_df,cols_to_transf)
    
    predict_df = predict_df[future_data_column_order]
    
    return predict_df
